observations.recommendation:
Submit a written justification or any issuances/documents/legal basis allowing the claim of TLB to an elected official at the end of the term of serving one elective position but still serving as an elected official in another elective position in the same LGU;

Refrain from payment of TLB unless the official and/or employee has submitted his/her intention to sever his connection with the agency or any mode of severances.

Retrieve the documents that would support the added back leave and the grant of double 3-day special leave to establish the accuracy of the computed TLB, otherwise cause the refund of the excess payment.

Submit the following documentary requirements on the grant and liquidation of the cash advance to attend the 2023 SGLG National Awarding Ceremony for the evaluation of the Audit Team:

Duly approved Office Order/Travel Order;
Duly approved Itinerary of Travel;
Approved Revised Itinerary of Travel, if the previously approved itinerary was not followed;
Certification from the Chief Accountants that previous cash advances have been fully liquidated and accounted for in the books;
Copy of the Office Order and the Supplemental Office Order or any proof supporting the change of schedule, if applicable;
Letter of invitation of the host/sponsoring agency/organization for the 16 department heads-attendees;
Liquidation Report;
Approved Certificate of Travel Completed; and
Certificate of Appearance or Attendance

Submit justification and the legal basis on the payment of the travel expenses of the 16 officials to attend the SGLG awarding ceremony despite the invitation limits only to three representatives.

We recommend and Management agreed to:
Require the Municipal Accountant and GSO to conduct reconciliation of their respective inventory records and locate the documents supporting the purchase of fuel, oil, and lubricants and its eventual consumption;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to adjust the books of accounts to bring the recorded inventory account to its accurate balance based on the results of reconciliation and submission of necessary documentations;
Submit the RPCI for all recorded inventory items to the Audit Team for further evaluation.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Require the Municipal Treasurer to prepare a duly certified list showing the names of the taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year which data should come from the RPTAR or Taxpayer’s Index Card maintained at the Municipal Treasurer’s Office;
Furnish the Municipal Accountant a copy of the certified list to serve as basis in recording the Real Property Tax Receivable and Special Education Tax Receivable accounts in the books;
Require the Municipal Accountant to record the receivables based on the list furnished by the Municipal Treasurer in order to recognize in the books an accurate and reliable data pursuant to 20 of the NGAS Manual, Volume 1; and
Finally, require the Municipal Accountant and Treasurer to reconcile their records and exclude those recorded receivables that have been already collected through advance payments.

The Inventory Committee and/or the personnel assigned in inventory taking to diligently conduct the physical count of items including those properties/items recorded in SEF books of the Municipal Government in order to provide a reliable RPCPPE;

Municipal Treasurer to begin the process of the disposal of the unserviceable properties and to identify the accountable person/ custodian of the missing/ non-existing items so that appropriate actions, such as filing of Request for RelieffromAccountability and other procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006 on the disposition of non-existing/ missing PPEs, shall be undertaken;

Municipal Accountant to:

Reclassify the items/ properties with costs that do not qualify with the capitalization threshold to appropriate expense accounts and those items erroneously classified as Other PPE to the proper PPE accounts; 

Make necessary adjustments on the respective labor cost of the PPEs constructed by administration. 

Direct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to trace the cost of each land indicated in the RPCPPE by retrieving the prior years’ records available.

Direct the Municipal Accountant:

To re-evaluate each payable account to ascertain the existence of actual claims and send confirmations to the claimants, if warranted, so that the required reversion of items, which had been in the books for two years and over, would be effected;

To identify the name of the creditors of those items under “accounts payable” and “returned of stale check” creditors, and create their individual ledgers instead;

To reassess the adjustment made pertaining to the loan amortization payments and effect correcting entry if necessary; and

To reclassify those transactions that do not fall under the accounts payable to their respective appropriate accounts. 

Henceforth, use the proper account code/title in recording financial liabilities in accordance with the Revised Chart of Accounts for Local Government Units.

We recommended and the Disbursing Officer agreed to submit the following documentary requirements on the grant and liquidation of the cash advance to attend the 2023 SGLG National Awarding Ceremony for the evaluation of the Audit Team:
Duly approved Office Order/Travel Order;
Duly approved Itinerary of Travel;
Approved Revised Itinerary of Travel, if the previously approved itinerary was not followed;
Certification from the Chief Accountants that previous cash advances have been fully liquidated and accounted for in the books;
Copy of the Office Order and the Supplemental Office Order or any proof supporting the change of schedule, if applicable;
Letter of invitation of the host/sponsoring agency/organization for the 16 department heads-attendees;
Liquidation Report;
Approved Certificate of Travel Completed; and
Certificate of Appearance or Attendance;
We recommended and the Municipal Mayor and other personnel concerned agreed to submit justification and the legal basis on the payment of the travel expenses of the 16 officials to attend the SGLG awarding ceremony despite the invitation limits only to three representatives.

The Municipal Accountant to secure the necessary supporting documents as proof that disbursements charged against the 20 per cent development fund are in connection with the implementation of developmental projects that contribute to the attainment of desirable socio-economic development and environmental outcomes of the LGU, and shall partake the nature of investment or capital expenditures;

The Municipal Accountant and Budget Officer to refrain from charging salaries and wages of job order personnel and other expenses that are administrative in nature under the 20 per cent DF; and

Strictly adhere with the provisions of DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 2020-1 and other pertinent rules and regulations.

We recommended that Management:
Direct all implementing office and the LDRRMO to properly utilize the LDRRMF based on the programs, projects and activities contained in the LDRRMF Plan and adherence with Item 5.0 and other provisions of NDRRMC-DBM-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1 dated March 25, 2013;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and Budget Officer to properly review the expenses charged against the LDRRMF and refrain from utilizing the fund for program, projects and activities not in accordance with the primary purpose for which the fund was established.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that the Management:
Submit the lacking documentary requirement mentioned above for the Audit Team’s verification to make a decision in the audit;
Henceforth, adhere with the documentary requirements prescribed under COA Circular No. 2012-001 and other pertinent rules and regulations before making any payment of terminal leave benefits.

Prepare MOA between the municipality and the Farmers’ Association for the operation of Barangay Food Terminal and implement the monitoring and inspection of the said project as required in COA Circular 2007-001 and the MOA between the DA-RFU 7 and the municipality;

Require the Accountant to maintain financial accounting records of the funds granted to NGO/PO to keep track of the progress of the project implementation, prepare and submit required periodic financial and physical status reports; and

Revisit the conditions of the MOA and come up with corrective measures to ensure compliance with the provisions of the MOA and COA Circular No. 2007-001for the ultimate attainment of its objectives.

Directed that:
.1	The Municipal Mayor constitute an Inventory Team that will initiate plans and spearhead the conduct of physical count of all the supplies and property of the LGU as mandated in Section 124 of the NGAS Manual;

2	The designated Property Custodian plan and conduct periodic physical inventory of the supplies and property of the LGU, awaiting the constitution of an inventory team by the Municipal Mayor.  The RPCPPE and RPCI prepared by the office of the Custodian, as a result of the inventory taking, shall be reconciled with the accounting records.  These Reports shall also be submitted to COA pursuant to Section 124 of NGAS Manual for LGU;

3	The Property Custodian to make and maintain a list of all the supplies and property of the LGU, with complete information thereof reflected therein like the name and description of the supply or property, serial number, property number, location, cost, date acquired/completed, etc.  The list shall be reconciled with the similar records in the accounting at least a quarter;

4	The Municipal Accountant to maintain Supplies, PPEs and other property Ledger Cards.  Ensure that all the PPEs in the list/schedule must contain complete information like the name and description of the supply or property, serial number, property number, location, cost, date acquired/completed, etc.  Reconcile the accounting records with the list/reports being kept by the Property Custodian at least quarterly;

5	The Property Custodian to property tag every PPE including the breeding stocks.  This will help in easy and fast monitoring of the assets and identification thereof in case a loss of the same;

6	The Property Custodian to provide PAR to every PPE issued to respective end users.  Accountability to the property redounds to the latter; and

7	Adhere to Sections 119, 120 and 124 of the NGAS Manual, Volume 1, Section 3(c), Chapter   V   of   the   Manual   on   Property Custodianship, and other pertinent laws, rules and regulations governing the conduct of physical count of properties, maintenance of records and submission of reports thereof to the Auditor.

Prepare MOA between the municipality and the Farmers’ Association for the operation of Barangay Food Terminal and implement the monitoring and inspection of the said project as required in COA Circular 2007-001 and the MOA between the DA-RFU 7 and the municipality;

Require the Accountant to maintain financial accounting records of the funds granted to NGO/PO to keep track of the progress of the project implementation, prepare and submit required periodic financial and physical status reports; and

Revisit the conditions of the MOA and come up with corrective measures to ensure compliance with the provisions of the MOA and COA Circular No. 2007-001for the ultimate attainment of its objectives.

